# Orchestrator — Run Setup

## Project identity
- **slug:** `civicq`
- **run dir:** `upwork-runs/civicq/`
- **demo path (local):** `../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/civicq/`
- **demo URL (live):** `https://michaelwegter.com/demos/civicq/`
- **work-sample route:** `/work-samples/civicq`
- **target feature richness:** 10 / 10 (full-featured, production-quality, the
  complete landing page built to spec with all three custom data visualizations
  working)

## What the client actually wants (startup brief)
CivicQ is a **nonpartisan civic information platform** (voting records, bill
activity, public statements pulled from official sources, "no spin, just the
record"). They need an **expert US-based front-end developer** to build the
**public-facing home page at civicq.org**, extending an existing staging
dark-mode design system (not redesigning it). All copy is final and provided in
a structured drop-in document; the dev is **building to spec**, not authoring
content or design.

The deliverable is a **10-section landing page with sticky navigation**, plus one
additional page (`civicq.org/methodology`):

1. Hero with video thumbnail + primary/secondary CTAs
2. Problem statement (single-column text)
3. Feature card grid (2×2, with LIVE / IN DEVELOPMENT status pills)
4. Scoring methodology with a custom data viz (6-dimension weighted chart)
5. Honest status disclosure (two-column: live vs. in-development)
6. Organization Hub section with wireframe mockup + email capture
7. Fundraising module with funds-breakdown graphic + GoFundMe CTA
8. Partners / Press / Orgs (three-column card section)
9. Feedback banner + footer
10. Sticky nav with anchor links + existing search/auth

### Hard requirements (the grading checklist)
- React or **Next.js** (stack listed: React, Next.js, JavaScript, Tailwind CSS)
- **Dark-mode design system matched precisely**, not redesigned
- **Fully responsive: 390px mobile / 1440px desktop**
- **Lighthouse 85+ on mobile**
- **Three custom data visualizations** (coded SVG or Recharts/D3):
  1. Six-dimension scoring chart (weighted bar or donut)
  2. $75K funds-breakdown graphic
  3. Organization Hub wireframe mockup
- **Email capture form** (Mailchimp/ConvertKit) **with CSV backup**
- **Analytics install** (Plausible or Fathom preferred)
- **WCAG 2.1 AA accessibility**
- The extra **/methodology page** (content provided)

### To-apply asks (the proposal must answer all four)
1. Portfolio (link the live demo + /work-samples/civicq)
2. Timeline estimate (their window is 2–4 weeks; give a concrete milestone plan)
3. **Approach to the three custom graphics** — say plainly that Michael builds
   them himself in code (no designer assets needed). The demo PROVES this by
   shipping all three as real coded visualizations.
4. Fixed price bid (their range is $3,500–$5,000; milestone payments welcome)

### Reading between the lines
- This is the rare posting where the demo IS the deliverable category. The single
  most persuasive move is to **build the actual landing page they describe** —
  all 10 sections, sticky nav, both pages, all three data viz, working email
  capture — so the proposal can say "here is your home page, already built and
  live, click it." That beats any amount of prose.
- "Matched precisely, not redesigned" + "all copy is final" means the client
  fears a freelancer who will go rogue on brand or rewrite their words. The demo
  and proposal should signal **discipline and spec-fidelity**: a restrained,
  professional civic-tech dark theme, placeholder copy that reads like real
  CivicQ copy (nonpartisan, factual, "just the record" tone), and visible respect
  for the "build to spec" framing.
- **Nonpartisan is the brand's whole identity.** Every word and visual must read
  as neutral, institutional, trustworthy. No red/blue partisan coding, no
  editorializing. Think official-record, data-forward, calm authority.
- "LIVE / IN DEVELOPMENT status pills" and the "honest status disclosure"
  section signal a brand that prides itself on **radical transparency about what
  works today vs. what's coming**. Honor that in the demo copy.
- **Hard launch dependency on a GoFundMe campaign** — the fundraising module and
  its $75K breakdown graphic are not decoration; they are launch-blocking. Treat
  that data viz and the GoFundMe CTA as first-class.
- US-based requirement: Michael qualifies (note it in the cover letter; do not
  belabor it).

## Plan of attack (phase ordering)
Recommended graph. Email capture with CSV backup is a real backend opportunity,
so a backend + live test add credibility, and richness is maxed — use
`with-deploy` + `with-ceo`:

`intake -> planner -> ceo -> researcher -> demo-builder -> deploy -> deploy-test -> media-capture -> proposal-writer -> evaluator`

Pair the CEO after planner (and again after demo-builder if the layout allows) to
keep ambition aligned with the 10/10 target and spec fidelity.

### Guidance per downstream phase
- **intake:** Capture every explicit requirement as a checklist item: the 10
  sections, the /methodology page, React/Next, precise dark-mode match, responsive
  390/1440, Lighthouse 85+ mobile, the **three** named data viz, email capture +
  CSV backup, analytics, WCAG 2.1 AA. Also capture the four to-apply asks
  (portfolio, timeline, graphics approach, fixed bid). Flag that brand assets are
  "provided" in real life but unavailable to us — the demo must invent a faithful
  stand-in dark civic-tech design system and note that production matches CivicQ's
  actual tokens.
- **planner:** This is a **full build, not a prototype** (richness 10). Hero
  feature = the complete 10-section landing page with **sticky anchor nav** and
  smooth scroll. The **three custom data visualizations are the centerpiece** and
  must be real, coded, and animated/interactive where sensible (the six-dimension
  weighted scoring chart, the $75K funds-breakdown graphic, the Org Hub wireframe
  mockup). Supporting features (within caps): (a) **working email capture** wired
  to **mw-backend** with a real persisted list + a CSV-export/backup endpoint
  (this directly proves the "Mailchimp/ConvertKit + CSV backup" requirement far
  better than a dead form), and (b) the **/methodology second page** + LIVE/IN-DEV
  status pills and the honest live-vs-in-dev disclosure. Add a lightweight
  privacy-respecting analytics stub (Plausible-style event hooks) to satisfy the
  analytics line. Define a **bespoke civic-tech dark design system** (neutral,
  institutional, data-forward — slate/ink backgrounds, a restrained accent or
  two, high-contrast legible type, NOT michaelwegter.com's mustard/cyan gallery
  theme). Produce the requirement→feature traceability matrix; every one of the
  10 sections plus both pages must trace to demo output.
- **researcher:** Pull conventions from real civic-data / govtech platforms
  (GovTrack, OpenSecrets, Ballotpedia, ProPublica, Vote Smart, Plural/LegiScan)
  and modern nonprofit dark-mode landing pages: neutral institutional palettes,
  data-viz idioms for scoring/weights and budget breakdowns, transparency-forward
  copy patterns. Confirm the **demo form** (self-contained static app is likely
  ideal here; a small Vite/React build is fine if the data viz warrants it — note
  base path `/demos/civicq/`). Identify the exact backend scaffold to clone:
  `spotify_blueprint.py` for the email-capture blueprint. Cap at ~6 fetches.
- **demo-builder:** Build into the demo path above. Ship **all 10 sections + the
  /methodology page**, sticky anchor nav with active-section highlighting, all
  **three coded data visualizations**, and a **working email capture** form. If
  backend greenlit, add ONE blueprint (`civicq_blueprint.py`: POST subscribe +
  GET csv-export), register in `server.py`, keep CORS open, don't touch
  auth/DB/other blueprints beyond what's needed. Responsive at 390 and 1440;
  semantic HTML, focus states, alt text, ARIA, and color contrast for **WCAG 2.1
  AA**; keep it lean for **Lighthouse 85+ mobile**. Self-test: build + load with
  no first-paint console errors.
- **deploy / deploy-test:** Push both repos if the blueprint was added. Playwright
  the live site: scroll through all 10 sections, click each sticky-nav anchor,
  verify the three data viz render, submit the email form and confirm it persists
  (and that CSV export returns rows), load /methodology. Emit VERDICT.
- **media-capture:** Hero flow = a top-to-bottom scroll of the finished landing
  page hitting the three data visualizations, plus a successful email-capture
  submission. Capture both mobile (390) and desktop (1440) framings if feasible.
- **proposal-writer:** Tailor deck + one-pager to the civic-tech / nonprofit
  audience using the demo's design language (neutral, institutional, factual).
  Answer all **four** to-apply asks explicitly: portfolio (the live demo link),
  timeline (concrete milestones inside their 2–4 week window, noting the GoFundMe
  hard-launch dependency), **graphics approach** (Michael codes all three himself,
  no designer assets needed — point at the live ones), and a **fixed price bid**
  inside $3,500–$5,000 with milestone structure. Embed the live demo link in BOTH
  the cover letter AND the deck. Map each of the 10 sections + both pages +
  every key requirement to what the demo shows. Note US-based.
- **evaluator:** Enforce the hard gates; confirm all 10 sections, both pages, all
  three data viz, email capture, accessibility, and the four to-apply answers are
  present and traceable.

## Quality guidance / risks to watch
- **Spec fidelity is the whole pitch.** The client explicitly fears a dev who
  redesigns or rewrites. Build exactly the 10 sections they listed, in order, with
  their structure (status pills, two-column disclosures, three-column cards). The
  demo should look like *their* product, not a Michael-flavored reinterpretation.
- **The three data visualizations are make-or-break** and the proposal must speak
  to them directly. Build all three as real, coded, accessible SVG/Recharts
  visuals — the six-dimension weighted scoring chart should clearly show the
  weights, the $75K breakdown should sum to $75K and read at a glance, and the Org
  Hub wireframe should look like an intentional product mockup, not a gray box.
- **Nonpartisan neutrality** in every pixel and word. No partisan color coding, no
  loaded language. Calm, official, data-first. This is itself a design constraint.
- **Email capture must actually work** at richness 10. Prefer mw-backend so a
  submitted email persists and a CSV export returns it — that proves the
  "Mailchimp/ConvertKit + CSV backup" requirement instead of just claiming it.
- **Accessibility + performance are graded requirements**, not nice-to-haves:
  WCAG 2.1 AA (contrast, focus, semantics, ARIA, reduced-motion respect) and a
  lean enough build to clear Lighthouse 85+ on mobile. Don't over-animate.
- **Brand-assets honesty.** CivicQ's real tokens/logo/staging are provided to the
  hired dev but unavailable to us. The demo uses a faithful stand-in dark
  civic-tech system; the proposal should state plainly that production matches
  CivicQ's actual design system and copy doc precisely. Never imply we have their
  real assets.
- **Writing rules:** no em/en dashes anywhere; Michael's voice; concrete, not
  generic; reference the live demo by name and link. Cohesive bespoke design
  across demo + one-pager + deck (civic-tech dark, not the portfolio look).
- **Budget:** 1 hero + ≤2 supporting features, ≤~12 files touched in the demo,
  3-min build timeout, ≤~6 research fetches, reflection retries ≤2. Disk is
  memory — pass file paths between phases, not contents.

## Definition of done (carry forward)
All 6 hard gates in CLAUDE.md must hold: every brief requirement (all 10
sections, both pages, three data viz, email capture + CSV, analytics, responsive,
WCAG 2.1 AA, Lighthouse 85+) addressed in the cover letter AND represented in the
demo/deck; demo builds with no first-paint console errors; demo resolves locally
and the live `/work-samples/civicq` route returns 200; demo link in cover letter
AND deck; cohesive bespoke civic-tech design with no em/en dashes; passing
`eval-report.md` with an empty/accepted fix list.

Setup complete. Next step: intake.
